occurrences.line_text: For any brybes, or threates of any to be wroken.
For any brybes, or threates of any to be wroken.
And life enioy for any composition.
That any yron eyes to see it would agrize.
To which they had no right, nor any wrongfull state.
That any man would nigh awhaped make.
Yet still he striues, ne any perill spares,
Which vnto any knight behappen may
Or change of loue for any worlds delight?
For guiftes of gold, or any worldly glee,
Ne any able was him to withstand,
Ne euer any found his match in might;
And if she hapt of any good to heare,
That had to any happily betid,
But if she heard of ill, that any did,
Or harme, that any had, then would she make
For what soeuer good by any sayd,
To hearke what any one did good report,
And if that any ill she heard of any,
And if that any ill she heard of any,
Through thicke and thin, vnfit for any Dame.
Then fearing any foeman there to meete:
Ne time would giue, nor any termes aby,
I neuer saw in any greater hope appeare.
Should weet of me, nor worke me any wrong.
Yet could she not deuise by any wit,
Too greatly grieue at any his vnlucky case.
Of lodging fit for any errant Knight,
(For he was swift as any Bucke in chace)
Least that the beasts sharpe teeth had any wound
Ne any dares with him for it debate.
For by no art, nor any leaches might
As any one, that liued in his daies,
Ne lodging would to any of them graunt:
She was borne free, not bound to any wight,
As no whit dreading any liuing wight;
Ne powre had to withstand, ne hope of any ayd.
So as he could not weld him any way.
Me list not die for any louers doole:
Them selues to any trade, as for to driue
Nor any wicked feend, that mote offend
Did care a whit, ne any liking lend:
By any skill out of his cruell hands;
Ne any will had thence to moue away,
Therefore I doe not any one enuy,
Nor am enuyde of any one therefore;
Impatient of any paramoure:
Ne any paines ne perill did he shonne,
Through which if any grace chaunst to arize
Both his estate, and loue from skill of any wight.
Nor any footing fynde for ouergrowen gras.
Not sparing wight, ne leauing any balke,
That sore her payn'd, by any to be drest,
And sore oppresse, ne any him doth spare:
Ne any left, that victorie to him enuide.
By all meanes shund to match with any forrein fere.
Ne euer any durst till then impose,
Ne euer could by any more be brought
Into like bands, ne maystred any more:
Ne any is, that may him now restraine,
Phoenix, and Aon, and Pelasgus old,
Her to behold do thither runne apace,
He left his stond, and her pursewd apace,
Fled to the wastfull wildernesse apace,
She could them nimbly moue, and after fly apace.
So turned her about, and fled away apace.
As I her, so he me pursewd apace,
The whiles false Archimarge and Atin fled apace.
Vnto his Tygres taile, and shot at him apace.
Apace he shot, and yet he fled apace,
Apace he shot, and yet he fled apace,
Christalline humour dropped downe apace.
From the swift Barry, tombling downe apace,
Shall to the vtmost mountaines fly apace:
Through thicke and thin her to pursew apace,
But left his loue to losse, and fled himselfe apace.
And the great waters gin apace to swell,
His former suit, and from them fled apace;
His dewy lockes did drop with brine apace,
They round about him gan to swarme apace,
Yet Talus after them apace did plie,
That after those two former rode apace,
Where so he fled, he followd him apace:
Into the wood was bearing her apace
Vnto his Inne began to draw apace;
Pursuing him apace with greedy speede,
But after him the wyld man ran apace
Playing on pypes, and caroling apace,
He pypt apace, whilest they him daunst about.
Pype iolly shepheard, pype thou now apace
She made me often pipe and now to pipe apace.
Liues any, that you hath thus ill apaid?
For whiles she spake, her great words did apall
And trembling terror did his hart apall,
So th'other did mens rash desires apall,
From her in flight, he found, that did him sore apall.
As if such pride the other could apall;
Lay now thy deadly Heben bow apart,
Much rueth me; but now put feare apart,
And drowne in dissolute delights apart,
And these rich heapes of wealth doest hide apart
That it in flames of Aetna wrought apart,
For nothing he from her reseru'd apart,
And in long Alba plast his throne apart,
But when apart (if euer her apart)
But when apart (if euer her apart)
And with her dolefull accent beare with him apart.
I spyde, where at the Idoles feet apart
That his sharpe sword he threw from him apart,
One day her Ladie, calling her apart,
Whose fellow he before had sent apart;
So taking them apart into his cell,
For that faire Ladies loue: past perils well apay.
And eke with gratefull seruice me right well apay.
For she is inly nothing ill apayd,
Surprisd her sense: she therewith well apayd,
Which if thou gaine, I shalbe well apayd.
To your disports: ill mote ye bene apayd.
And then lay musing long, on that him ill apayd.
Or ill apayd, or much dismayd ye be,
So bore her quite away, nor well nor ill apayd.
To leaue his loue he should be ill apayd,
Who louers will deceiue. Thus was the ape,
Apes, Lions, ï¿½/-gles, Owles, fooles, louers, children, Dames.
Some like to hounds, some like to Apes, dismayd,
Of great Apollo, shew thy famous might
And thence Apollo King of Leaches brought.
Apollo came; who soone as he had sought
And for Apolloes honor highly herried.
That could the stoutest courage haue appald;
Beheld, it much appald her troubled spright:
And when him list the raskall routes appall,
That her misshaped parts did them appall,
Her gracious words their rancour did appall,
Ne wonder, if these did the knight appall;
Would make to melt, or pitteously appall;
Did all that youthly rout so much appall,
Therewith her wrathfull courage gan appall,
An huge great Lyon lay, that mote appall
Therewith Grandtorto selfe I did appall,
Yet no whit more appalled for the same,
And griesly wounds that him appalled sore.
This their request the Captaine much appalled;
Did vse to hide, and plaine apparaunce shonne:)
And of my kingdome heire apparaunt bee:
But Fury was full ill appareiled
Downe taking, her therein appareled,
And the tall trees with leaues apparelled,
The wals were round about apparelled
And oft of error did himselfe appeach:
That his vngentle hoste n'ote him appeach
Did her appeach, and to her more disgrace,
Which them appeached, prickt with guilty shame,
Vnto the Church, their prayers to appeale,
But with entire affection and appearaunce plaine.
Soone as appeard safe opportunitie:
But that their natures bad appeard in both:
Soone as my loathed loue appeard in sight,
In smithes fire-spitting forge, and nayles like clawes appeard.
And earely ere the dawning day appeard,
And fierce he still appeard, the more he did him thresh.
There there (said Britomart) a fresh appeard
Nor wight appear'd, but wastefull emptinesse,
The morrow next appeard with ioyous cheare,
To them appear'd, with shield and armour fit;
After each beautie, that appeard in sight,
Him dead behight, as he to all appeard,
In th'arm-pit full, that through both sides the wound appeard.
Appear'd in place, with all his noble crew:
Appear'd in place, the which each other did outgoe.
Like to the ruddie morne appeard in sight,
Right plaine appeard, though she it would dissemble,
Ne in his face or bloud or life appeard,
Which close appeard in that rude brutishnesse,
And none appear'd of all that raskall rout,
Appear'd in heauen, into the field they came,
But if the least appear'd, her eyes she streight reprieued.
Of all that vision, which to her appeard,
That of his shape appear'd no litle moniment.
The morrow next appear'd, with purple hayre
Appear'd like Aspis sting, that closely kils,
For the rare hope which in his yeares appear'd,
Yet dwelling in her eye, to her appeard,
Appeard for people in nor out to pas,
Who rough, and blacke, and filthy did appeare,
Vpon him fell: he no where doth appeare,
For neuer did such brightnesse there appeare,
As when iust time expired should appeare.
They might appeare, when he their soules shall saue.
Whom I from far see on the walles appeare
Which as an Eagle, seeing pray appeare,
Of late deuoured bodies did appeare,
The morrow next gan early to appeare,
The ioyous day gan early to appeare,
As bright as doth the morning starre appeare
But neither silke nor siluer therein did appeare.
He wo[n]der would much more: yet such to some appeare.
In whom great rule of Temp'raunce goodly doth appeare.
As lump of lead, and made darke clouds appeare;
And in her face faire peace, and mercy doth appeare.
Did all she might, more pleasing to appeare.
Ne thenceforth life ne courage did appeare,
By whom a litle skippet floting did appeare.
For not one puffe of wind there did appeare,
Said then the Palmer, Lo where does appeare
Such wondrous powre did in that staffe appeare,
Of th'Oceans fruitfull froth, did first appeare:
The secret signes of kindled lust appeare,
Mixed with manly sternnesse did appeare
Did sparckle forth great light, and glorious did appeare.
Her tender babe, it seeing safe appeare,
Tell me some markes, by which he may appeare,
To let the secret of her hart to her appeare.
On one, that worthy may perhaps appeare;
And yet was loth to let her purpose plaine appeare.
That whilome wont in women to appeare?
That shortly he a great Lord did appeare,
The furthest North, that did to them appeare:
As Hellene, when she saw aloft appeare
For loue in thousand monstrous formes doth oft appeare.
Yet liuing creature none she saw appeare:
That by his gate might easily appeare;
In rags, that naked nigh she did appeare,
That mote to none but to the warie wise appeare.
Thereof did in his frouning face appeare:
Deeming them doughtie as they did appeare,
How may these rimes, so rude as doth appeare,
Ne lesse his skill in weapons did appeare,
So many Ladies sought, as shall appeare;
And to the last vnconquer'd did appeare;
Now base and contemptible did appeare,
Full blacke and griesly did his face appeare,
The things that day most minds, at night doe most appeare.
Like to a golden border did appeare,
Where this same cursed caytiue did appeare,
A foule and lothsome creature did appeare;
And well perform'd, as shall appeare by his euent.
For they so like in person did appeare,
Or did misdoubt some ill, whose cause did not appeare.
The waters play and pleasant lands appeare,
That in her cheekes made roses oft appeare:
And records of antiquitie appeare,
With glittering spangs, that did like starres appeare,
So did he, and then plaine it did appeare,
Some blisfull houres at last must needes appeare;
As when two sunnes appeare in the azure skye,
By which that glorie gotten doth appeare.
Within his mouth a blacke spot doth appeare,
Which well I proue, as shall appeare by triall,
How that three warlike persons did appeare,
Yet that his guilt the greater may appeare,
The iustest man aliue, and truest did appeare.
There did appeare vnto her heauenly spright
Whose porch, that most magnificke did appeare,
Yet did appeare rare beautie in her face,
Yet sith he heard but one, that did appeare,
By which if that no champion doe appeare,
And beautifull, as glories beames appeare,
That from close friends, that dar'd not to appeare,
Soone as he did within the listes appeare,
Did vnderneath him like a pond appeare,
The one of them, that elder did appeare,
I neuer saw in any greater hope appeare.
And make their welcome to them well appeare:
Yet in his bodie made no wound nor bloud appeare.
And by rude tokens made to her appeare
Like troubled ghost did dreadfully appeare,
It crackt throughout, yet did no bloud appeare;
The goodly threasures of nature appeare:
Her goodly thighes, whose glorie did appeare
And this sweet peace, whose lacke did then appeare.
The playnes all waste and emptie did appeare:
In which what filth and ordure did appeare,
From top to toe no place appeared bare,
That from his head no place appeared to his feete.
Well it appeared, to haue beene of old
Ne drop of bloud appeared shed to bee,
Tho when appeared the third Morrow bright,
The art, which all that wrought, appeared in no place.
So through the Christall waues appeared plaine:
And in his port appeared manly hardiment.
At him, that first appeared in his sight:
Vnder the which, her feet appeared plaine,
With noise whereof the Lady forth appeared
On th'other side her foe appeared soone in sight.
But soone as he appeared to their vew,
Where none appeares can make her selfe a way:
Then first the coale of kindly heat appeares
Nor drop of bloud in all his face appeares
The drearie image of sad death appeares:
That well (me seemes) appeares, by that of late
Ne liuing aide for her on earth appeares,
That like a pined ghost he soone appeares.
They all are wandred much; that plaine appeares.
Not farre in sea; of which the one appeares
That way betwixt them none appeares in sight;
That well in courteous Calidore appeares,
That in thy face appeares and gratious goodlyhead.
Lo this my cause of griefe to you appeares;
That well appeares in this discourteous knight,
Whose borrowed beautie now appeareth plaine
Honour is least, where oddes appeareth most.
By miracle, not yet appearing playne,
Appearing like the mouth of Orcus griesly grim.
Ne might his ranckling paine with patience be appeasd.
That during life will neuer be appeasd.
Not all content, yet seemd she to appease
Haue vowd you to defend. Now then your plaint appease.
Did him appease; then downe his taile he hong
For thy appease your griefe and heauie plight,
When she her Squire heard speake, she gan appease
Yet algates mote he soft himselfe appease,
Appease his heat, or hastie passage stay;
So pleased, did his wrathfull purpose faire appease.
Himselfe appease, and issewd forth on shore:
Which in his land he lately did appease,
As those ye blame, yet may it nought appease
Besought him his great courage to appease,
He gan to cast how to appease the same,
Whereby to seeke some meanes it to appease.
In waylfull plaints, that none was to appease;
But with thy bloud thou shalt appease the spright
She parted thence, her anguish to appease.
Stroue to appease him, and perswaded long:
And all the way the Prince sought to appease
Doe them afflict, which no man can appease,
What she had said: so her she soone appeased,
With which she for the present was appeased,
So was their discord by this doome appeased,
And were not, that the Prince did him appeaze,
Hath hither brought, for succour to appele;
He gan that Ladie strongly to appele
A man of yeares yet fresh, as mote appere,
And so did let her goodly visage to appere.
And in that monstrous wise did to the world appere.
And bad before his soueraine Lord appere:
Then all his former parts did earst appere.
The which in floods and fountaines doe appere,
That forth out of an hill fresh gushing did appere.
Vnto a place, whose pleasaunce did appere
Well knowne to appertaine to Florimell,
For death t'adward I ween'd did appertaine
To whom they answer'd, as did appertaine,
That to her selfe that threasure appertained;
So that it to the looker appertaynd;
Whose name was Appetite; he did bestow
Of appetite with meates of euery sort,
Their feruent appetites they quenched had,
Of meates and drinkes their appetites suffiz'd,
Here eke that famous golden Apple grew,
The golden Apple, cause of all their wrong,
What time the golden apple was vnto him brought.
Loaden with fruit and apples rosie red,
Their fruit were golden apples glistring bright,
And fruitfull apples to haue borne awhile,
And euery feend his busie paines applide,
Their pleasaunt tunes they sweetly thus applide;
And all the while sweet birdes thereto applide
Her gentle speach applide, that in short space
And thereto all his power and might applide:
To whom his course he hastily applide,
Yet was the stroke so forcibly applide,
And did his yron brond so fast applie,
And many salues did to his sore applie,
And I likewise in vaine doe salues to you applie.
Of his fiers foe, him to a tree applies,
Well searcht, eftsoones he gan apply reliefe
Whereas he meant his corrosiues to apply,
Ne other worldly busines did apply;
And all the while sweete Musicke did apply
Who euer doth to temperaunce apply
Ne cared she her course for to apply:
And to them does the steddy helme apply,
Of which were twentie sonnes, which did apply,
As that, which strong affections do apply
They all that charge did feruently apply,
Therefore old Syre thy course do thereunto apply.
As diuerse wits to diuers things apply;
(Said she) and though no reason may apply
And sent in haste for Tryphon, to apply
And costly Cordialles she did apply,
And her flit Palfrey did so well apply
And now so fast his feet he did apply,
Which the bold Virgin seeing, gan apply
At least it faire endeuour will apply.
O spare thy happy dayes, and them apply
Of loue full manie lessons did apply,
That toward them his course seem'd to apply,
Whereby she might apply some medicine;
Nathlesse for all the powre she did apply,
How for Iolas sake he did apply
And all his powre doth thereunto apply:
Behinde, beside, before, as he it list apply.
To the sea shore he gan his way apply,
Which he could wisely vse, and well apply,
Ne could her liking to his loue apply,
Vnto his first exploite he did him selfe apply.
So well he did his busie paines apply,
During which time, that wyld man did apply
What euer formes ye list thereto apply,
And euermore his speach he did apply
He daily did apply him selfe to donne
By force, he gan his hundred tongues apply,
With like conditions to their kinds applyde:
Whose flying feet so fast their way applyde,
Which done, he balmes and herbes thereto applyde,
And counsell sage in steed thereof to him applyde.
Eftsoones her steps she thereunto applyde,
She weend, and wondrous gladnesse to her hart applyde.
He with good thewes and speaches well applyde,
This well I wote, that she so well applyde
Then all their helpes they busily applyde,
And all his powre applyed thereunto,
A-waite whereto their seruice he applyes,
Which speaches she applying to the scope
The fourth appointed by his office was,
The senselesse corse appointed for the graue.
Eftsoones he came vnto th'appointed place,
Till that at length vpon th'appointed day,
Within a groue appointed him to meete;
From the first point of his appointed sourse,
Bound like a beast appointed to the stall:
To doe those workes, to them appointed dew:
Who bringing them to their appointed place,
For she presuming on th'appointed tyde,
Appointed by that mightie Faerie Prince,
Appointed for Irenas death before,
And from the earth, appointed haue her place,
Appointed to attend her dewly day and night.
In leaches craft, by great Appolloes lore,
Then gan Authority her to appose
Where she for secret purpose did appoynt
How then shall I, Apprentice of the skill,
Him to assault, nor once approach him nie,
Whereto approaching nigh, they heard the sound
Who soone as them approaching he descride,
But soone as th'other nigh approaching, vewed
Who soone as she him saw approaching neare
Of his grim face, were from approaching scard;
To whom Sir Calidore approaching nye,
An armed Knight approaching to the place,
Durst not approch, for he was deadly made,
Durst not approch for dread, which she misdeem'd,
Ne durst approch him nigh, to touch, or once assay.
Though she thy Lady be, approch thee neare;
Approch, albe his drowsie den were next;
And inward griefe, he fiercely gan approch,
Till that the Squire gan nigher to approch;
But labour lost it was, to weene approch him neare.
To which nor fish nor fowle did once approch,
And to him beckned, to approch more neare,
None of them rashly durst to her approch,
And now she gan approch to the sea shore,
Approch to her, ne keepe her company,
Of his approch, and gan him selfe prepare
He durst not nigh approch, but kept aloofe,
Who seeing her approch gan forward set,
To which when now they gan approch in sight,
Yet would not neare approch in daungers eye,
Thereto approch, ne filth mote therein drowne:
Once to approch to her in priuity,
Tho when no more could nigh to him approch,
Whereto whenas they now approched neare,
He soone approched, panting, breathlesse, whot,
Then pittie, he in hast approched to the shore.
And being on his way, approched neare,
Their visages imprest, when they approched neare.
And now they nigh approched to the sted,
Who as they now approched nigh at hand,
But ere that it to him approched neare,
Till to his castle they approched neare.
To whom as they approched, they espide
To whom when he approched neare in sight,
So forth they past, till they approched ny
To which when she approched, thus she sayd;
Tho whenas he approched nigh in vew,
Who as he vnto him approched nye,
Tho to the place when they approched nye,
But he him fast pursuing, soone approched neare.
Would faine haue fled, ne durst approchen neare,
But yet durst not for dread approchen nie,
Ne none can suffer to approchen neare:
Ne that approcheth nigh the wide descent,
The messenger approching to him spake,
To whom approching she to her gan call,
Approching nigh, she wist it was the same,
The knight approching nigh, of him inquerd
The Witch approching gan him fairely greet,
Who when these two approching he aspide,
Approching nigh, he reared high afore
To them approching, thus the knight bespake:
The knight approching nigh thus to her said,
Whiles the sad pang approching she does feele,
Approching, first the Hag did thrust away,
Approching nigh, he neuer stayd to greete,
Fiercely approching, to him lowdly cride,
And to her bed approching, first she prooued,
The knight approching, sternely her bespake;
Whom when as nigh approching she espyde,
To whom approching, well he mote perceiue
